I think that dtao incentivizes emission to subnets based on current price. However in markets investors buy stocks based on expected future price. Expected future price is not the same as current price. We use the market price as a proxy basically assuming that current price is the best estimation of future price. However, when we do this we overly incentivize short term price thinking — because it’s automatically incentivized by the protocol.  Where as in a real market you would focus on long term thinking.
This actually biases subnets that “do nothing and don’t spend and money” because that maximizes current price, which in turn bolsters current price.
In a “normal market” you wouldn’t be paid or incentivized by maintaining a high price if there is no plan towards future high prices.
In short, we may be suffering the consequences of our choice of proxy “price”
And where we may find a solution is actually by measuring relative increases in Tao liquidity relative to emission. Or, in other words, growth that is irrespective or emission.
So for instance, subnet 5 is not experiencing high relative pool growth when Tao emission rate is included. It is growing slowly given its Tao emission.

Shorting won’t work, no matter how it’s designed, because shorting requires borrowing tokens from someone. Systems that allow this always demand collateral, and with extremely low liquidity the collateral requirement would be very high—making short squeezes extremely profitable.

As for centralization, yes, that’s a valid concern. But my proposal was for the community to elect a council through voting, so it wouldn’t be 100% centralized. The real issue is that tagging scam or low-value subnets is trivial for a human, and very few would reasonably object. However, it’s essentially impossible for an automated system relying only on on-chain data, because that data simply doesn’t exist in sufficient quality to make proper assessments.

Blockchain only solves a few pieces of the decentralization puzzle, and the technology simply isn’t there yet. Until it evolves further, there’s no other effective option.

messages.content: Technically the goal isn’t subnet elimination, it’s driving down their emissions to zero so they don’t suck up emissions for just existing. Now that deregs are back on the menu, elimination could happen as a secondary consequence, which is great.

I agree that the goal is not to eliminate subnets, but simply to tag the low-quality ones so they no longer leech emissions. I was against deregistration because the concept of token ownership—on which legal frameworks around the world rely—is very strong. Tokens held in wallets that users control shouldn’t be forcibly sold against their will. Otherwise, Bittensor risks crossing the line of being considered “decentralized enough,” which could expose it to stricter regulations.

Liquidity pools, on the other hand, don’t belong to anyone. It is OTF’s prerogative to feed or not feed those pools at its discretion, without any ethical or legal concerns. Nevertheless, deregistration has already been implemented—so at this point, we can only hope for the best.
Wasn't the intent of dTAO to "let the market decide". Kinda of funny how these conversations continue to go full circle.

The market currently has no way of “deciding” that a subnet is getting too many emissions. That’s the problem. Shorting fixes this. Build it into the protocol. Bunch of smart people here, I’m sure sure we can figure out how to make it work.

Sure it does. Emissions are dictated by allocating stake to a specific subnet. If the market deems a subnet to be worthless then it "should"continue to have stake removed resulting in less and less emissions. Thats the design anyways. Clearly degen behavior has proven to conflict.

I’ve argued elsewhere that a totally free market does not—and cannot—exist. In reality, there are always trade-offs. My pre-dtao idea was that EMA price isn’t a good base for emissions because it depends on liquidity. In a thin pool a tiny trade can move the mark; in a thick pool owners can sit on a flat price for ages. Both can look “healthy” on a price-EMA even when there’s no real demand, which is how we end up with dead subnets that hoard their own α and coast.

A better option may be to switch from price-EMA to an EMA of net TAO flow into the α/TAO pool, counting only organic swaps (exclude protocol emissions and root sells). This measures whether people are actually buying into the subnet over time. It’s much harder to game because you’d need sustained TAO inflows across epochs, not a one-off mark. It’s also liquidity-agnostic: if buyers aren’t coming, flow won’t be positive, no matter how thin or thick the pool is. And it self-corrects—when interest fades, the flow average falls and emissions follow.

This change reinforces subnets as TAO sinks. When users buy α with TAO and then stake, more TAO gets parked inside pools and treasuries while α gets locked, shrinking the liquid TAO float. That immobilization of supply is exactly what TAO holders want: more of the token working inside the network, less sitting idle and sellable, and emissions directed to places attracting real, persistent demand rather than engineered stability.

It is not a full solution for predicting future performance of subnets to determine emissions, but less gameable than price.

this is why we brought up the synced inflation model in a paper a while back. the value of the rewards eventually exceeds the value of the injection. inevitably leading to burns, which reduces the max supply. 

syncing the inflation takes care of this automatically, by ensuring that a_out scales down with max(a_in) (keeping a_out value in sync with tao_in value each block), and removing the separate alpha halvings based on alpha issuance. 

the consequence is you don't hit 21m alpha as a result. but you could argue that the vast majority will never hit 21m alpha if they burn a large % over decades. ultimately, these are the rules and we have to work within them by finding creative solutions to the problems

Thanks. What's the limiting factor to stop us from hitting the 21 million alpha?

under a synced inflation model
- if you register your subnet after the first tao halving, you'll never hit 21m. because the inflation is based on remaining tao to emit. `current alpha supply + (2 * remaining tao to emit)`
- current subnets, if they don't burn alpha, would actually exceed 21m alpha. because they started when there was more than 10.5 mil tao to emit. this is seen as a massive red flag so that's why our proposal got a lot of pushback.

under an async inflation model
- unless your subnet starts pretty late into the future, and as long as you don't do any burns, you should hit 21m alpha. that's the short answer
- the consequence though is that you might get a "paper money" effect, since in the far future, you could have a subnet starting with e.g. 1 a_out per block, and 0.03125 a_in per block. emission % might be 10% (meaning price is 0.1), and therefore tao_in per block is 0.003125 tao_in. the value of the alpha rewards each block is 32x the value of the tao injection. causes huge price impact with buys and sells. idk for certain how tricky the situation would be , but I imagine it won't be easy, and they'd likely burn a very large % of alpha each block to mitigate the sell pressure
